1. Distributed Web Infrastructure

A user wants to access the website www.foobar.com using a web browser.
The browser sends a DNS request to resolve the domain name.
DNS returns the IP address of the load balancer.

The load balancer (HAProxy) receives the HTTP request and distributes it
to one of the backend servers.

The load balancer is added to distribute incoming traffic between multiple
servers in order to improve performance and availability.

This infrastructure contains two servers.
Each server runs:
- A web server (Nginx)
- An application server
- The application codebase
- A MySQL database

Having two servers allows the system to handle more traffic and provides
better availability compared to a single server.

The load balancer uses a Round Robin distribution algorithm.
This algorithm forwards requests to each server sequentially,
ensuring traffic is evenly distributed.

The load balancer is configured in an Active-Active setup.
In Active-Active, all backend servers handle traffic at the same time.
In Active-Passive, only one server handles traffic while the other waits
as a backup.

The database is configured as a Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) cluster.
The Primary database handles write operations.
The Replica database copies data from the Primary and handles read operations.

The Primary node is responsible for inserting, updating, and deleting data.
The Replica node is used to read data and improve performance
but does not handle write operations.

Issues with this infrastructure:

There is still a Single Point of Failure (SPOF) at the load balancer.
If the load balancer fails, the entire system becomes unavailable.

There are security issues because there is no firewall to protect the servers
and no HTTPS to encrypt traffic.

There is no monitoring system to detect failures or performance issues,
which makes it difficult to maintain reliability.
